[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/data-pipeline] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In mathematics, particularly graph theory, and computer science, a **directed acyclic graph** (**DAG**) is a directed graph with no directed cycles.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] That is, it consists of vertices and edges (also called *arcs*), with each edge directed from one vertex to another, such that following those directions will never form a closed loop.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is a DAG if and only if it can be topologically ordered, by arranging the vertices as a linear ordering that is consistent with all edge directions.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] DAGs have numerous scientific and computational applications, ranging from biology (evolution, family trees, epidemiology) to information science (citation networks) to computation (scheduling).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs are also called **acyclic directed graphs** or **acyclic digraphs**.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph is formed by vertices and by edges connecting pairs of vertices, where the vertices can be any kind of object that is connected in pairs by edges.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In the case of a directed graph, each edge has an orientation, from one vertex to another vertex.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A walk in a directed graph is a (finite or infinite) sequence $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc )$ of vertices such that each consecutive pair $(v_{i},v_{i+1})$ is connected by a directed edge.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A path is a walk where all vertices are distinct.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle is a walk $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc ,v_{n})$ where the only repeated vertex is $v_{n}=v_{1}$ , meaning the last vertex equals the first vertex.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph is a directed graph that has no cycles.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The reachability relation of a DAG can be formalized as a partial order ≤ on the vertices of the DAG.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In this partial order, two vertices u and v are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* exactly when there exists a directed path from u to v in the DAG; that is, when u can reach v (or v is reachable from u).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] However, different DAGs may give rise to the same reachability relation and the same partial order.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, a DAG with two edges *u* → *v* and *v* → *w* has the same reachability relation as the DAG with three edges *u* → *v*, *v* → *w*, and *u* → *w*.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Both of these DAGs produce the same partial order, in which the vertices are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* ≤ *w*.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a DAG is the graph with the most edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG, and may therefore be thought of as a direct translation of the reachability relation ≤ into graph-theoretic terms.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In this way, every finite partially ordered set can be represented as a DAG.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction of a DAG is the graph with the fewest edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the covering relation of the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] It is a subgraph of the DAG, formed by discarding the edges *u* → *v* for which the DAG also contains a longer directed path from u to v.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Like the transitive closure, the transitive reduction is uniquely defined for DAGs.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for a directed graph that is not acyclic, there can be more than one minimal subgraph with the same reachability relation.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Transitive reductions are useful in visualizing the partial orders they represent, because they have fewer edges than other graphs representing the same orders and therefore lead to simpler graph drawings.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A Hasse diagram of a partial order is a drawing of the transitive reduction in which the orientation of every edge is shown by placing the starting vertex of the edge in a lower position than its ending vertex.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] goes from earlier in the ordering (upper left) to later in the ordering (lower right).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is acyclic if and only if it has a topological ordering.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A topological ordering of a directed graph is an ordering of its vertices into a sequence, such that for every edge the start vertex of the edge occurs earlier in the sequence than the ending vertex of the edge.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph that has a topological ordering cannot have any cycles, because the edge into the earliest vertex of a cycle would have to be oriented the wrong way.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, every graph with a topological ordering is acyclic.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Conversely, every directed acyclic graph has at least one topological ordering.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The existence of a topological ordering can therefore be used as an equivalent definition of a directed acyclic graphs: they are exactly the graphs that have topological orderings.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, this ordering is not unique; a DAG has a unique topological ordering if and only if it has a directed path containing all the vertices, in which case the ordering is the same as the order in which the vertices appear in the path.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The family of topological orderings of a DAG is the same as the family of linear extensions of the reachability relation for the DAG, so any two graphs representing the same partial order have the same set of topological orders.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The graph enumeration problem of counting directed acyclic graphs was studied by Robinson (1973).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] (2004) proved, that the same numbers count the (0,1) matrices for which all eigenvalues are positive real numbers.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The proof is bijective: a matrix A is an adjacency matrix of a DAG if and only if *A* + *I* is a (0,1) matrix with all eigenvalues positive, where I denotes the identity matrix.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Because a DAG cannot have self-loops, its adjacency matrix must have a zero diagonal, so adding I preserves the property that all matrix coefficients are 0 or 1.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A *multitree* (also called a *strongly unambiguous graph* or a *mangrove*) is a DAG in which there is at most one directed path between any two vertices.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Equivalently, it is a DAG in which the subgraph reachable from any vertex induces an undirected tree.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A *polytree* (also called a *directed tree*) is a multitree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] An *arborescence* is a polytree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree away from a particular vertex, called the *root* of the arborescence.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Topological sorting is the algorithmic problem of finding a topological ordering of a given DAG.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Kahn's algorithm for topological sorting builds the vertex ordering directly.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] It maintains a list of vertices that have no incoming edges from other vertices that have not already been included in the partially constructed topological ordering; initially this list consists of the vertices with no incoming edges at all.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Then, it repeatedly adds one vertex from this list to the end of the partially constructed topological ordering, and checks whether its neighbors should be added to the list.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The algorithm terminates when all vertices have been processed in this way.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, a topological ordering may be constructed by reversing a postorder numbering of a depth-first search graph traversal.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Any undirected graph may be made into a DAG by choosing a total order for its vertices and directing every edge from the earlier endpoint in the order to the later endpoint.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The resulting orientation of the edges is called an acyclic orientation.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Different total orders may lead to the same acyclic orientation, so an n-vertex graph can have fewer than *n*! acyclic orientations.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The number of acyclic orientations is equal to |*χ*(−1)|, where χ is the chromatic polynomial of the given graph.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Any directed graph may be made into a DAG by removing a feedback vertex set or a feedback arc set, a set of vertices or edges (respectively) that touches all cycles.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] However, the smallest such set is NP-hard to find.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] An arbitrary directed graph may also be transformed into a DAG, called its condensation, by contracting each of its strongly connected components into a single supervertex.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] When the graph is already acyclic, its smallest feedback vertex sets and feedback arc sets are empty, and its condensation is the graph itself.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a given DAG, with n vertices and m edges, may be constructed in time *O*(*mn*) by using either breadth-first search or depth-first search to test reachability from each vertex.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, it can be solved in time *O*(*n**ω*) where *ω* < 2.373 is the exponent for matrix multiplication algorithms; this is a theoretical improvement over the *O*(*mn*) bound for dense graphs.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In all of these transitive closure algorithms, it is possible to distinguish pairs of vertices that are reachable by at least one path of length two or more from pairs that can only be connected by a length-one path.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction consists of the edges that form length-one paths that are the only paths connecting their endpoints.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, the transitive reduction can be constructed in the same asymptotic time bounds as the transitive closure.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The closure problem takes as input a vertex-weighted directed acyclic graph and seeks the minimum (or maximum) weight of a closure – a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The problem may be formulated for directed graphs without the assumption of acyclicity, but with no greater generality, because in this case it is equivalent to the same problem on the condensation of the graph.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Some algorithms become simpler when used on DAGs instead of general graphs, based on the principle of topological ordering.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, it is possible to find shortest paths and longest paths from a given starting vertex in DAGs in linear time by processing the vertices in a topological order, and calculating the path length for each vertex to be the minimum or maximum length obtained via any of its incoming edges.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for arbitrary graphs the shortest path may require slower algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm or the Bellman–Ford algorithm, and longest paths in arbitrary graphs are NP-hard to find.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graph representations of partial orderings have many applications in scheduling for systems of tasks with ordering constraints.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] An important class of problems of this type concern collections of objects that need to be updated, such as the cells of a spreadsheet after one of the cells has been changed, or the object files of a piece of computer software after its source code has been changed.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, a dependency graph is a graph that has a vertex for each object to be updated, and an edge connecting two objects whenever one of them needs to be updated earlier than the other.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle in this graph is called a circular dependency, and is generally not allowed, because there would be no way to consistently schedule the tasks involved in the cycle.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependency graphs without circular dependencies form DAGs.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, when one cell of a spreadsheet changes, it is necessary to recalculate the values of other cells that depend directly or indirectly on the changed cell.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] For this problem, the tasks to be scheduled are the recalculations of the values of individual cells of the spreadsheet.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependencies arise when an expression in one cell uses a value from another cell.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In such a case, the value that is used must be recalculated earlier than the expression that uses it.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Topologically ordering the dependency graph, and using this topological order to schedule the cell updates, allows the whole spreadsheet to be updated with only a single evaluation per cell.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Similar problems of task ordering arise in makefiles for program compilation and instruction scheduling for low-level computer program optimization.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A somewhat different DAG-based formulation of scheduling constraints is used by the program evaluation and review technique (PERT), a method for management of large human projects that was one of the first applications of DAGs.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In this method, the vertices of a DAG represent milestones of a project rather than specific tasks to be performed.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Instead, a task or activity is represented by an edge of a DAG, connecting two milestones that mark the beginning and completion of the task.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Each such edge is labeled with an estimate for the amount of time that it will take a team of workers to perform the task.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The longest path in this DAG represents the critical path of the project, the one that controls the total time for the project.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Individual milestones can be scheduled according to the lengths of the longest paths ending at their vertices.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph may be used to represent a network of processing elements.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In this representation, data enters a processing element through its incoming edges and leaves the element through its outgoing edges.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, in electronic circuit design, static combinational logic blocks can be represented as an acyclic system of logic gates that computes a function of an input, where the input and output of the function are represented as individual bits.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, the output of these blocks cannot be used as the input unless it is captured by a register or state element which maintains its acyclic properties.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuit schematics either on paper or in a database are a form of directed acyclic graphs using instances or components to form a directed reference to a lower level component.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuits themselves are not necessarily acyclic or directed.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Dataflow programming languages describe systems of operations on data streams, and the connections between the outputs of some operations and the inputs of others.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] These languages can be convenient for describing repetitive data processing tasks, in which the same acyclically-connected collection of operations is applied to many data items.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] They can be executed as a parallel algorithm in which each operation is performed by a parallel process as soon as another set of inputs becomes available to it.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In compilers, straight line code (that is, sequences of statements without loops or conditional branches) may be represented by a DAG describing the inputs and outputs of each of the arithmetic operations performed within the code.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] This representation allows the compiler to perform common subexpression elimination efficiently.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] At a higher level of code organization, the acyclic dependencies principle states that the dependencies between modules or components of a large software system should form a directed acyclic graph.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Feedforward neural networks are another example.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Graphs in which vertices represent events occurring at a definite time, and where the edges always point from an earlier time vertex to a later time vertex, are necessarily directed and acyclic.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The lack of a cycle follows because the time associated with a vertex always increases as you follow any directed path in the graph, so you can never return to a vertex on a path.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] This reflects our natural intuition that causality means events can only affect the future, they never affect the past, and thus we have no causal loops.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] An example of this type of directed acyclic graph are those encountered in the causal set approach to quantum gravity though in this case the graphs considered are transitively complete.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In the version history example below, each version of the software is associated with a unique time, typically the time the version was saved, committed or released.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In the citation graph examples below, the documents are published at one time and can only refer to older documents.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Sometimes events are not associated with a specific physical time.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Provided that pairs of events have a purely causal relationship, that is edges represent causal relations between the events, we will have a directed acyclic graph.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, a Bayesian network represents a system of probabilistic events as vertices in a directed acyclic graph, in which the likelihood of an event may be calculated from the likelihoods of its predecessors in the DAG.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, the moral graph of a DAG is the undirected graph created by adding an (undirected) edge between all parents of the same vertex (sometimes called *marrying*), and then replacing all directed edges by undirected edges.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Another type of graph with a similar causal structure is an influence diagram, the vertices of which represent either decisions to be made or unknown information, and the edges of which represent causal influences from one vertex to another.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In epidemiology, for instance, these diagrams are often used to estimate the expected value of different choices for intervention.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] That is in any application represented by a directed acyclic graph there is a causal structure, either an explicit order or time in the example or an order which can be derived from graph structure.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] This follows because all directed acyclic graphs have a topological ordering, i.e. there is at least one way to put the vertices in an order such that all edges point in the same direction along that order.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Family trees may be seen as directed acyclic graphs, with a vertex for each family member and an edge for each parent-child relationship.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Despite the name, these graphs are not necessarily trees because of the possibility of marriages between relatives (so a child has a common ancestor on both the mother's and father's side) causing pedigree collapse.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The graphs of matrilineal descent (mother-daughter relationships) and patrilineal descent (father-son relationships) are trees within this graph.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Because no one can become their own ancestor, family trees are acyclic.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The version history of a distributed revision control system, such as Git, generally has the structure of a directed acyclic graph, in which there is a vertex for each revision and an edge connecting pairs of revisions that were directly derived from each other.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] These are not trees in general due to merges.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In many randomized algorithms in computational geometry, the algorithm maintains a *history DAG* representing the version history of a geometric structure over the course of a sequence of changes to the structure.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance in a randomized incremental algorithm for Delaunay triangulation, the triangulation changes by replacing one triangle by three smaller triangles when each point is added, and by "flip" operations that replace pairs of triangles by a different pair of triangles.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The history DAG for this algorithm has a vertex for each triangle constructed as part of the algorithm, and edges from each triangle to the two or three other triangles that replace it.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] This structure allows point location queries to be answered efficiently: to find the location of a query point q in the Delaunay triangulation, follow a path in the history DAG, at each step moving to the replacement triangle that contains q.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The final triangle reached in this path must be the Delaunay triangle that contains q.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In a citation graph the vertices are documents with a single publication date.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The edges represent the citations from the bibliography of one document to other necessarily earlier documents.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The classic example comes from the citations between academic papers as pointed out in the 1965 article "Networks of Scientific Papers" by Derek J. de Solla Price who went on to produce the first model of a citation network, the Price model.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In this case the citation count of a paper is just the in-degree of the corresponding vertex of the citation network.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] This is an important measure in citation analysis.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Court judgements provide another example as judges support their conclusions in one case by recalling other earlier decisions made in previous cases.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A final example is provided by patents which must refer to earlier prior art, earlier patents which are relevant to the current patent claim.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] By taking the special properties of directed acyclic graphs into account, one can analyse citation networks with techniques not available when analysing the general graphs considered in many studies using network analysis.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance transitive reduction gives new insights into the citation distributions found in different applications highlighting clear differences in the mechanisms creating citations networks in different contexts.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Another technique is main path analysis, which traces the citation links and suggests the most significant citation chains in a given citation graph.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The Price model is too simple to be a realistic model of a citation network but it is simple enough to allow for analytic solutions for some of its properties.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Many of these can be found by using results derived from the undirected version of the Price model, the Barabási–Albert model.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] However, since Price's model gives a directed acyclic graph, it is a useful model when looking for analytic calculations of properties unique to directed acyclic graphs.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, the length of the longest path, from the n-th node added to the network to the first node in the network, scales as $\ln(n)$ .
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs may also be used as a compact representation of a collection of sequences.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In this type of application, one finds a DAG in which the paths form the given sequences.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] When many of the sequences share the same subsequences, these shared subsequences can be represented by a shared part of the DAG, allowing the representation to use less space than it would take to list out all of the sequences separately.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, the directed acyclic word graph is a data structure in computer science formed by a directed acyclic graph with a single source and with edges labeled by letters or symbols; the paths from the source to the sinks in this graph represent a set of strings, such as English words.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Any set of sequences can be represented as paths in a tree, by forming a tree vertex for every prefix of a sequence and making the parent of one of these vertices represent the sequence with one fewer element; the tree formed in this way for a set of strings is called a trie.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Similarly, a binary search tree can be viewed as a rooted DAG where paths represent sorted orderings of keys, though it lacks the path-merging compression found in more complex DAGs.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic word graph saves space over a trie by allowing paths to diverge and rejoin, so that a set of words with the same possible suffixes can be represented by a single tree vertex.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The same idea of using a DAG to represent a family of paths occurs in the binary decision diagram, a DAG-based data structure for representing binary functions.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] In a binary decision diagram, each non-sink vertex is labeled by the name of a binary variable, and each sink and each edge is labeled by a 0 or 1.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] The function value for any truth assignment to the variables is the value at the sink found by following a path, starting from the single source vertex, that at each non-sink vertex follows the outgoing edge labeled with the value of that vertex's variable.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/directed-acyclic-graph] Just as directed acyclic word graphs can be viewed as a compressed form of tries, binary decision diagrams can be viewed as compressed forms of decision trees that save space by allowing paths to rejoin when they agree on the results of all remaining decisions.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] A properly designed ETL system extracts data from source systems and enforces data type and data validity standards and ensures it conforms structurally to the requirements of the output.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems can also deliver data in a presentation-ready format so that application developers can build applications and end users can make decisions.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The ETL process is often used in data warehousing.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] ETL systems commonly integrate data from multiple applications (systems), typically developed and supported by different vendors or hosted on separate computer hardware.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The separate systems containing the original data are frequently managed and operated by different stakeholders.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] For example, a cost accounting system may combine data from payroll, sales, and purchasing.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] ETL and its variant ELT (extract, load, transform), are increasingly used in cloud-based data warehousing.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Applications involve not only batch processing, but also real-time streaming.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] ETL processing involves extracting the data from the source system(s).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] In many cases, this represents the most important aspect of ETL, since extracting data correctly sets the stage for the success of subsequent processes.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Most data-warehousing projects combine data from different source systems.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Each separate system may also use a different data organization and/or format.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The streaming of the extracted data source and loading on-the-fly to the destination database is another way of performing ETL when no intermediate data storage is required.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] An intrinsic part of the extraction involves data validation to confirm whether the data pulled from the sources has the correct/expected values in a given domain (such as a pattern/default or list of values).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] If the data fails the validation rules, it is rejected entirely or in part.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The rejected data is ideally reported back to the source system for further analysis to identify and to rectify incorrect records or perform data wrangling.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] In the data transformation stage, a series of rules or functions are applied to the extracted data in order to prepare it for loading into the end target.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] An important function of transformation is data cleansing, which aims to pass only "proper" data to the target.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The challenge when different systems interact is in the relevant systems' interfacing and communicating.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Character sets that may be available in one system may not be in others.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The load phase loads the data into the end target, which can be any data store including a simple delimited flat file or a data warehouse.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Depending on the requirements of the organization, this process varies widely.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Some data warehouses may overwrite existing information with cumulative information; updating extracted data is frequently done on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Other data warehouses (or even other parts of the same data warehouse) may add new data in a historical form at regular intervals – for example, hourly.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] To understand this, consider a data warehouse that is required to maintain sales records of the last year.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] This data warehouse overwrites any data older than a year with newer data.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] However, the entry of data for any one year window is made in a historical manner.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The timing and scope to replace or append are strategic design choices dependent on the time available and the business needs.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] More complex systems can maintain a history and audit trail of all changes to the data loaded in the data warehouse.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] As the load phase interacts with a database, the constraints defined in the database schema – as well as in triggers activated upon data load – apply (for example, uniqueness, referential integrity, mandatory fields), which also contribute to the overall data quality performance of the ETL process.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Audit reports (for example, on compliance with business rules.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Archive (Extreme, space-efficient compression for very rarely used, old data.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] ETL processes can involve considerable complexity, and significant operational problems can occur with improperly designed ETL systems.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The range of data values or data quality in an operational system may exceed the expectations of designers at the time validation and transformation rules are specified.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Data profiling of a source during data analysis can identify the data conditions that must be managed by transform rules specifications, leading to an amendment of validation rules explicitly and implicitly implemented in the ETL process.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Data warehouses are typically assembled from a variety of data sources with different formats and purposes.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] As such, ETL is a key process to bring all the data together in a standard, homogeneous environment.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Design analysis should establish the scalability of an ETL system across the lifetime of its usage – including understanding the volumes of data that must be processed within service level agreements.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The time available to extract from source systems may change, which may mean the same amount of data may have to be processed in less time.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems have to scale to process terabytes of data to update data warehouses with tens of terabytes of data.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Increasing volumes of data may require designs that can scale from daily batch to multiple-day micro batch to integration with message queues or real-time change-data-capture for continuous transformation and update.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Unique keys play an important part in all relational databases, as they tie everything together.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] A unique key is a column that identifies a given entity, whereas a foreign key is a column in another table that refers to a primary key.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Keys can comprise several columns, in which case they are composite keys.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] In many cases, the primary key is an auto-generated integer that has no meaning for the business entity being represented, but solely exists for the purpose of the relational database – commonly referred to as a surrogate key.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] As there is usually more than one data source getting loaded into the warehouse, the keys are an important concern to be addressed.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] For example: customers might be represented in several data sources, with their Social Security number as the primary key in one source, their phone number in another, and a surrogate in the third.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Yet a data warehouse may require the consolidation of all the customer information into one dimension.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] A recommended way to deal with the concern involves adding a warehouse surrogate key, which is used as a foreign key from the fact table.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Usually, updates occur to a dimension's source data, which must be reflected in the data warehouse.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] If the primary key of the source data is required for reporting, the dimension already contains that piece of information for each row.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] If the source data uses a surrogate key, the warehouse must keep track of it even though it is never used in queries or reports; it is done by creating a lookup table that contains the warehouse surrogate key and the originating key.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] This way, the dimension is not polluted with surrogates from various source systems, while the ability to update is preserved.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The lookup table is used in different ways depending on the nature of the source data.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] A new dimension row is added with the new state of the source system, while the previous dimension row is updated to reflect it is no longer active and time of deactivation.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] ETL vendors benchmark their record-systems at multiple TB (terabytes) per hour (or ~1 GB per second) using powerful servers with multiple CPUs, multiple hard drives, multiple gigabit-network connections, and much memory.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] In real life, the slowest part of an ETL process usually occurs in the database load phase.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Databases may perform slowly because they have to take care of concurrency, integrity maintenance, and indices.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Still, even using bulk operations, database access is usually the bottleneck in the ETL process.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Whether to do certain operations in the database or outside may involve a trade-off.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] For example, removing duplicates using `distinct` may be slow in the database; thus, it makes sense to do it outside.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] On the other side, if using `distinct` significantly (x100) decreases the number of rows to be extracted, then it makes sense to remove duplications as early as possible in the database before unloading data.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] A common source of problems in ETL is a big number of dependencies among ETL jobs.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] For example, job "B" cannot start while job "A" is not finished.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] One can usually achieve better performance by visualizing all processes on a graph, and trying to reduce the graph making maximum use of parallelism, and making "chains" of consecutive processing as short as possible.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Again, partitioning of big tables and their indices can really help.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Another common issue occurs when the data are spread among several databases, and processing is done in those databases sequentially.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Sometimes database replication may be involved as a method of copying data between databases – it can significantly slow down the whole process.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] This approach allows processing to take maximum advantage of parallelism.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] For example, if you need to load data into two databases, you can run the loads in parallel (instead of loading into the first – and then replicating into the second).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Sometimes processing must take place sequentially.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] For example, dimensional (reference) data are needed before one can get and validate the rows for main "fact" tables.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Some ETL software implementations include parallel processing.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] This enables a number of methods to improve overall performance of ETL when dealing with large volumes of data.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] All three types of parallelism usually operate combined in a single job or task.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] An additional difficulty comes with making sure that the data being uploaded is relatively consistent.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Because multiple source databases may have different update cycles (some may be updated every few minutes, while others may take days or weeks), an ETL system may be required to hold back certain data until all sources are synchronized.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Likewise, where a warehouse may have to be reconciled to the contents in a source system or with the general ledger, establishing synchronization and reconciliation points becomes necessary.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Data warehousing procedures usually subdivide a big ETL process into smaller pieces running sequentially or in parallel.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] To keep track of data flows, it makes sense to tag each data row with "row_id", and tag each piece of the process with "run_id".
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] In case of a failure, having these IDs help to roll back and rerun the failed piece.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Best practice also calls for *checkpoints*, which are states when certain phases of the process are completed.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Once at a checkpoint, it is a good idea to write everything to disk, clean out some temporary files, log the state, etc.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] An established ETL framework may improve connectivity and scalability.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] A good ETL tool must be able to communicate with the many different relational databases and read the various file formats used throughout an organization.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] ETL tools have started to migrate into enterprise application integration, or even enterprise service bus, systems that now cover much more than just the extraction, transformation, and loading of data.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Many ETL vendors now have data profiling, data quality, and metadata capabilities.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] A common use case for ETL tools include converting CSV files to formats readable by relational databases.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] A typical translation of millions of records is facilitated by ETL tools that enable users to input CSV-like data feeds/files and import them into a database with as little code as possible.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] ETL tools are typically used by a broad range of professionals – from students in computer science looking to quickly import large data sets to database architects in charge of company account management, ETL tools have become a convenient tool that can be relied on to get maximum performance.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] ETL tools in most cases contain a GUI that helps users conveniently transform data, using a visual data mapper, as opposed to writing large programs to parse files and modify data types.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] While ETL tools have traditionally been for developers and IT staff, research firm Gartner wrote that the new trend is to provide these capabilities to business users so they can themselves create connections and data integrations when needed, rather than going to the IT staff.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Gartner refers to these non-technical users as Citizen Integrators.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] In online transaction processing (OLTP) applications, changes from individual OLTP instances are detected and logged into a snapshot, or batch, of updates.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] An ETL instance can be used to periodically collect all of these batches, transform them into a common format, and load them into a data lake or warehouse.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Data virtualization can be used to advance ETL processing.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The application of data virtualization to ETL allowed solving the most common ETL tasks of data migration and application integration for multiple dispersed data sources.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Virtual ETL operates with the abstracted representation of the objects or entities gathered from the variety of relational, semi-structured, and unstructured data sources.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] ETL tools can leverage object-oriented modeling and work with entities' representations persistently stored in a centrally located hub-and-spoke architecture.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Such a collection that contains representations of the entities or objects gathered from the data sources for ETL processing is called a metadata repository and it can reside in memory or be made persistent.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] By using a persistent metadata repository, ETL tools can transition from one-time projects to persistent middleware, performing data harmonization and data profiling consistently and in near-real time.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Extract, load, transform (ELT) is a variant of ETL where the extracted data is loaded into the target system first.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] The architecture for the analytics pipeline shall also consider where to cleanse and enrich data as well as how to conform dimensions.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Some of the benefits of an ELT process include speed and the ability to more easily handle both unstructured and structured data.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Ralph Kimball and Joe Caserta's book *The Data Warehouse ETL Toolkit*, (Wiley, 2004), which is used as a textbook for courses teaching ETL processes in data warehousing, addressed this issue.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Cloud-based data warehouses like Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, Microsoft Azure Synapse Analytics, and Snowflake provide highly scalable computing power.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] This lets businesses forgo preload transformations and replicate raw data into their data warehouses, where it can transform them as needed using SQL.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] After having used ELT, data may be processed further and stored in a data mart.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Most data integration tools skew towards ETL, while ELT is popular in database and data warehouse appliances.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/extract-transform-load] Similarly, it is possible to perform TEL (Transform, Extract, Load) where data is first transformed on a blockchain (as a way of recording changes to data, e.g., token burning) before extracting and loading into another data store.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] A **job scheduler** is a computer application for controlling unattended background program execution of jobs.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] This is commonly called **batch scheduling**, as execution of non-interactive jobs is often called batch processing, though traditional *job* and *batch* are distinguished and contrasted; see that page for details.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] Other synonyms include **batch system**, **distributed resource management system** (**DRMS**), **distributed resource manager** (**DRM**), and, commonly today, **workload automation** (**WLA**).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] The data structure of jobs to run is known as the job queue.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] Modern job schedulers typically provide a graphical user interface and a single point of control for definition and monitoring of background executions in a distributed network of computers.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] Increasingly, job schedulers are required to orchestrate the integration of real-time business activities with traditional background IT processing across different operating system platforms and business application environments.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] If software from a completely different area includes all or some of those features, this software can be considered to have job scheduling capabilities.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] Most operating systems, such as Unix and Windows, provide basic job scheduling capabilities, notably by at and batch, cron, and the Windows Task Scheduler.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] Web hosting services provide job scheduling capabilities through a control panel or a webcron solution.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] Many programs such as DBMS, backup, ERPs, and BPM also include relevant job-scheduling capabilities.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] Operating system ("OS") or point program supplied job-scheduling will not usually provide the ability to schedule beyond a single OS instance or outside the remit of the specific program.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] These advanced capabilities can be written by in-house developers but are more often provided by suppliers who specialize in systems-management software.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] There are many concepts that are central to almost every job scheduler implementation and that are widely recognized with minimal variations: jobs, dependencies, job streams, and users.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] Beyond the basic, single OS instance scheduling tools there are two major architectures that exist for Job Scheduling software.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] Job schedulers have been one of the major components of IT infrastructure since the early mainframe systems.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] At first, stacks of punched cards were processed one after the other, hence the term "batch processing".
[src:aws-data-pipeline/job-scheduler] Various schemes are used to decide which particular job to run.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/orchestration-computing] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/orchestration-computing] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/orchestration-computing] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/orchestration-computing] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/orchestration-computing] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/orchestration-computing] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/orchestration-computing] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/orchestration-computing] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/orchestration-computing] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] From a more abstract perspective, workflow may be considered a view or representation of real work.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] The flow being described may refer to a document, service, or product that is being transferred from one step to another.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Workflows may be viewed as fundamental building blocks to be combined with other parts of an organization's structure, such as information technology, teams, projects, and hierarchies.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] The development of the workflow concept occurred across several loosely defined, overlapping eras.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] The modern history of workflows can be traced to Frederick Taylor and Henry Gantt, although the term "workflow" was not used in this context during their lifetimes.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] One of the earliest instances of the term "work flow" was in a railway engineering journal from 1921.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Taylor and Gantt launched the study of the deliberate, rational organization of work, primarily in the context of manufacturing.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] This gave rise to time and motion studies.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Related concepts include job shops and queuing systems (Markov chains).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] The 1948 book *Cheaper by the Dozen* introduced the emerging workflow concept to the context of family life.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] The invention of the typewriter and the copier helped spread the study of the rational organization of labor from the manufacturing shop floor to the office.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Filing and other sophisticated systems for managing physical information flows evolved.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Several events likely contributed to the development of formalized information workflows.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] First, the field of optimization theory matured and developed mathematical optimization techniques.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] For example, Soviet mathematician and economist Leonid Kantorovich developed the seeds of linear programming in 1939 through efforts to solve a plywood manufacturer's production optimization issues.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Second, World War II and the Apollo program drove process improvement forward with their demands for the rational organization of work.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Juran led to a focus on quality, first in Japanese companies, and more globally from the 1980s.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] There were various movements ranging from total quality management to Six Sigma, and then more qualitative notions of business process re-engineering.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] This led to more efforts to improve workflows in both knowledge economy sectors and manufacturing.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Thought leaders recognized variable demands on workflows when they considered the theory of critical paths and moving bottlenecks.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Basu and Kumar noted that the term "workflow management" referred to tasks associated with the flow of information through the value chain rather than the flow of material goods: they characterise the definition, analysis and management of information as "workflow management".
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] The transmission of information from one organization to another is a critical issue in this inter-organizational context and raises the importance of tasks they describe as "validation", "verification" and "data usage analysis".
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] A workflow management system (WfMS) is a software system for creating, executing, and monitoring a defined sequence of processes and tasks, with the broad goals of increasing productivity, reducing costs, becoming more agile, and improving information exchange within an organization.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] These systems may be process-centric or data-centric, and they may also represent the workflow as graphical maps.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] A workflow management system may also include an extensible interface so that external software applications can be integrated, providing support for wide area workflows that provide both faster response times and improved productivity.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] The workflow concept is closely related to several fields in operations research and other areas that study the nature of work either quantitatively or qualitatively, such as artificial intelligence (in particular, the sub-discipline of AI planning) and ethnography.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] The term "workflow" is more commonly used in particular industries like printing, as well as professional domains such as clinical laboratories.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] It may have particular specialized meanings in these areas.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] **Planning and scheduling**: A plan is a description of the logically necessary, partially ordered set of activities required to accomplish a specific goal given certain starting conditions.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] A plan, when augmented with a schedule and resource allocation calculations, completely defines a particular *instance* of systematic processing in pursuit of a goal.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] A workflow may be viewed as an often optimal or near-optimal realization of the mechanisms required to execute the same plan repeatedly.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] **Flow control**: This is a control concept applied to workflows, to distinguish from static control of buffers of material or orders, to mean a more dynamic control of flow speed and flow volumes in motion and in process.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Such orientation to dynamic aspects is the basic foundation to prepare for more advanced job shop controls, such as just-in-time or just-in-sequence.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] **In-transit visibility**: This monitoring concept applies to transported material as well as to work in process or work in progress, i.e., workflows.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Insurance claims processing is an example of an information-intensive, document-driven workflow.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Wikipedia editing can be modeled as a stochastic workflow.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] The Getting Things Done system is a model of personal workflow management for information workers.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] In software development, support and other industries, the concept of *follow-the-sun* describes a process of passing unfinished work across time zones.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] In scientific experiments, the overall process (tasks and data flow) can be described as a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] This DAG is referred to as a workflow, e.g., Brain Imaging workflows.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] In healthcare data analysis, a workflow can be identified or used to represent a sequence of steps that comprise a complex data analysis.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] In service-oriented architectures, an application can be represented through an executable workflow, where different, possibly geographically distributed, service components interact to provide the corresponding functionality under the control of a workflow management system.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] In shared services, an application can be in the practice of developing robotic process automation (called RPA or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0 based on artificial intelligence) which results in the deployment of attended or unattended software agents to an organization's environment.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] These software agents, or robots, are deployed to perform pre-defined structured and repetitive sets of business tasks or processes.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Artificial intelligence software robots are deployed to handle unstructured data sets and are deployed after performing and deploying robotic process automation.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Measurement: Many of the concepts used to measure scheduling systems in operations research are useful for measuring general workflows.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] These include throughput, processing time, and other regular metrics.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Specialized connotations: The term "workflow" has specialized connotations in information technology, document management, and imaging.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Since 1993, one trade consortium specifically focused on workflow management and the interoperability of workflow management systems, the Workflow Management Coalition.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Scientific workflow systems: These found wide acceptance in the fields of bioinformatics and cheminformatics in the early 2000s, when they met the need for multiple interconnected tools that handle multiple data formats and large data quantities.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Also, the paradigm of scientific workflows resembles the well-established practice of Perl programming in life science research organizations, making this adoption a natural step towards more structured infrastructure setup.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Human-machine interaction: Several conceptualizations of mixed-initiative workflows have been studied, particularly in the military, where automated agents play roles just as humans do.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] For innovative, adaptive, and collaborative human work, the techniques of human interaction management are required.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Workflow analysis: Workflow systems allow users to develop executable processes with no familiarity with formal programming concepts.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Automated workflow analysis techniques can help users analyze the properties of user workflows to conduct verification of certain properties before executing them, e.g., analyzing flow control or data flow.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Examples of tools based on formal analysis frameworks have been developed and used for the analysis of scientific workflows and can be extended to the analysis of other types of workflows.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Several workflow improvement theories have been proposed and implemented in the modern workplace.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Resource evaluation (both physical and human) is essential to evaluating hand-off points and creating smoother transitions between tasks.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] A workflow can usually be described using formal or informal flow diagramming techniques and displays directed flows between processing steps.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Components can only be plugged together if the output of one previous (set of) component(s) is equal to the mandatory input requirements of the following component(s).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Thus, the essential description of a component actually comprises only input and output that are described fully in terms of data types and their meaning (semantics).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] The algorithms' or rules' descriptions need only be included when there are several alternative ways to transform one type of input into one type of output – possibly with different accuracy, speed, etc.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] When the components are non-local services that are invoked remotely via a computer network, such as Web services, developers must consider additional descriptors (such as QoS and availability).
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] A workflow application is a software application that automates a process or processes to some degree.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] These processes are usually business-related but can be any process that requires a series of steps to be automated via software.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Some process steps may require human intervention, such as development and approval of custom text, but functions that can be automated should be handled by the application.
[src:aws-data-pipeline/workflow] Advanced applications allow users to introduce new components into the operation.
